his is the key. The host global setting is causing your problem.

Current values:

host                             = 192.168.0.180
indirect.agent.lb.algorithm      = static
indirect.agent.lb.check.interval = 0

Because host=192.168.0.180, every KVM agent is told by CloudStack to connect to 192.168.0.180, which is why agent.properties keeps getting rewritten to:

host=192.168.0.180@static

When apcs1 goes down, the agents have nowhere to reconnect.

Option 1 (Recommended for your setup)

Since you already have HAProxy on 192.168.0.182:8080 and cannot proxy 8250, configure CloudStack to advertise both management servers instead of a single IP.

Update the global setting:

UPDATE configuration
SET value='192.168.0.180,192.168.0.181'
WHERE name='host';

Then restart the management service on both servers:

systemctl restart cloudstack-management

After that, restart one KVM agent and check:

grep "^host=" /etc/cloudstack/agent/agent.properties

Ideally, it should contain both management servers instead of only 192.168.0.180.

If that does not work

Some CloudStack versions do not support multiple IPs in the host global setting when indirect.agent.lb.algorithm=static.

In that case, there are only two supported production options:

Option A

Use a dedicated TCP load balancer (HAProxy) for port 8250 on a separate node, so it can own the VIP without conflicting with the management server.

Option B

Configure the CloudStack agent manually with multiple hosts (if your agent version supports it), instead of relying on the management server to rewrite agent.properties.

Please check your CloudStack version

Run:

cloudstack-setup-management --version

or

rpm -q cloudstack-management

Also, on one KVM host run:

rpm -q cloudstack-agent

I know you're on 4.21.0.0, but I want the exact build. There was a change in agent failover behavior in the 4.21.x series, and with the exact version I can tell you whether host=ip1,ip2 is officially supported or whether you need to use a different load-balancing algorithm.
